Strength

Tensile Strength: Resistance to being pulled apart.

Compressive Strength: Resistance to being compressed.

Shear Strength: Resistance to forces that cause sliding between planes.

Elasticity

Ability of a material to return to its original shape after the force is removed.

Young’s Modulus (E): Measures stiffness.

Plasticity

Ability of a material to undergo permanent deformation without breaking.

Important for shaping metals in manufacturing.

Hardness

Resistance to surface indentation, scratching, or wear.

Common tests: Brinell, Rockwell, Vickers.

Toughness

Ability to absorb energy before fracturing.

Combines strength and ductility.
